      <div xml:id="NA92-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu piriviṭai vēṟupaṭṭa kiḻattikkut tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE, who was changed in the time of separation, said to [her] confidante.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA92">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            uḷḷār kollō tōḻi tuṇaiyoṭu</l>
<l>            vēṉi lōtip pāṭunaṭai vaḻalai</l>
<l>            varimā ṉukumpiṉ vāṭi yavaṇa</l>
<l>            vaṟaṉporuntu kuṉṟat tucci kavāaṉ</l>
<l>            vēṭṭac cīṟū rakaṉkaṭ kēṇip </l>
<l>            payaniraik keṭutta maṇinīrp pattar</l>
<l>            puṉṟalai maṭappiṭi kaṉṟō ṭāra</l>
<l>            vilkaṭin tūṭṭiṉa peyaruṅ</l>
<l>            kolkaḷiṟ ṟoruttal curaṉiṟan tōrē.</l>
        </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Won't he remember, friend,</l>
<l>– the one who traversed the desert of the killing elephant bulls</l>
<l rend="indent2">that return, after having been chased away by the bow(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vil-kaṭintu</term>: this phrase is explained in a peculiar way by T.V.G., namely in the sense that <term xml:lang="ta">vil</term> would here mean a lid put on the well to protect it, which is taken away by the elephants in order to get at the water. Actually, the absolutive would speak in T.V.G.'s favour, since the subject should be the elephant, but there are so many counter-examples that this argument does not count for much.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent3">with bits [of water](?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ūṭṭiṉa peyarum</term>: construction is tricky here, but the parallel in NA 90.8 <term xml:lang="ta">(aḻutaṉaḷ peyarum</term> ... <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟu makaḷ</term>; cf. also NA 370.9, 399.8) suggests to take this as a case of <term xml:lang="ta">muṟṟeccam</term> plus <term xml:lang="ta">peyareccam</term> and take <term xml:lang="ta">kaḷiṟṟu oruttal</term> as subject (with the slightly strange consequence that we have to take them as plural). The idea would be, then, that the male elephants go take water from the trough in order to take it back to their females, in the process of which they are disturbed by the villagers carrying bows (if not T.V.G.’s suggestion has to be favoured; vgl. last note).</note> for the ruddy-headed inexperienced</l>
<l rend="indent3">she-elephants with [their] calves to become full,</l>
<l rend="indent2">from the trough of sapphire water raised for the yielding herd<note place="foot">Or, with another sandhi split, <term xml:lang="ta">nirai keṭutta</term>: “for the yielding herd to be destroyed”, that is, the milk-giving cows for whom the water was actually meant to be.</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">from the wide-eyed well in the desired small village</l>
<l rend="indent2">on the slope near the summit of the hill approached by draught,</l>
<l rend="indent">the striped animals of that place(?)<note place="foot">How are we supposed to construe line 2? The variant taken by the printed editions (a different interpretation of the same grapheme: <term xml:lang="ta">vari maral</term>) is as puzzling: "the striped bowstring hemp of that place fading like banana leaves".</note> fading like banana leaves,</l>
<l rend="indent">the sleepy-gaited serpent, the chameleon in summer,</l>
<l rend="indent4">with [its] mate?</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
